  "title": "The Highest Engagement Rate Posts From Pittsburgh Small Businesses",
  "subtitle": "Ranked by engagement as a percentage of follower count, not absolute likes. The punching-above-weight list.",
  "angle": "Pittsburgh's IG posts with the strongest reach relative to their account size. Small businesses can beat national chains here.",
  "intro": "The engagement rate list does not care how many followers you have. It cares how hard each post worked. To build this ranking, we took every Instagram post from the Pittsburgh businesses we cover, added likes, comments, and a weighted share of video plays, then divided by follower count. A neighborhood coffee shop with 2,800 followers that moves 40 percent of its audience on a single post beats a regional chain with half a million followers and a fraction of that response. That is the whole premise.\n\nThe results are specific and a little surprising. Delanie's Coffee in Shadyside, with roughly 23,000 followers, topped the list at 39.29 percent on a caption that was essentially a thank-you note to a photographer before a honky tonk night. Spot of Coffee, a 2,800-follower shop, landed both second place (39.03 percent) and fifth (20.38 percent), the only business to crack the top five twice. Page's, at nearly 104,000 followers, held third at 27.94 percent on a pickle split sundae announcement that apparently broke people's brains in the best way.\n\nThirty posts, 17 businesses, a two-post cap per account. Issue 02 will expand the dataset and start tracking whether these numbers hold, or whether this quarter was just a very good moment for small Pittsburgh coffee shops and frozen novelties.",
